        ],
        [
          "Regression",
          "MOOC",
          "E-Learning",
          "4831 MOOC learners",
          "6 Distinct MOOCs",
          "Survey",
          "None Specified",
          "[Age, Gender: Female, Education: PhD, Education: Master’s, Education: Professional, Education: Bachelor’s, Occupation: Student, Occupation: Employed, Experience with topic, Online Courses Started, Online Courses Finished, Time Commitment, Complete all assesments, Complete all lectures, OLEI: Research Revelant, OLEI: Job Relevant, OLEI School Relevant, OLEI: Earn Certificate, OLEI: Prestigious uni./instru., OLEI: Meet new People, OLEI: Take with others, OLEI: Personal Growth, OLEI: Experience MOOC, OLEI:  Fun and Challenge, OLEI: Improve Spanish, OLEI: Career Change, OLEI: General Interest]",
          "Authors start by colleting data from surveys and then use correlation analysis to see which constructs are more conducive to different outcomes in the course. \n\nThis analysis sub-sequently followed by a Regression analysis to see how each of the variables extracted actually contributes to each one of the different SRL constructs.",
          "Elastic-Net Regression",
          "-",
          "-",
          "SRL constructs vary with motivation to enter the MOOC and with previous acaemic background. \n\nCertificate, Meet People, Prestige are all among the most relevant motivators for higher SRL skills. ",
          "Goal Setting and Strategic Planning are especially relevant for success in MOOCs. \n\nLEarners with strong SRL skills tend to revisit course content to retest their learning. \n\nHelp-seeking seems to have a negative relationship with success. These results are somewhat suprising… since prior literature usually points to success when there is motivation to work with learners - this may come from the fact that, while a study buddy may be an interesting approach, the fact is that online communitites usually don’t have a structured support system to foster that environment,",
          "Authors extract data from surveys over different MOOC students and see the effect of their answers on multiple SRL constructs.\n\nThey make multiple analysis over the validity of the answers… identify the most relevant predcitors of each SRL construct using a LASSO regression.",
          "Lasso Regression only\n\nDoes not consider Behavioral Data\n\nPotential problems with the validity of the constructs\n\nMOOC-only context\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 6
    }
  ],
